Problem Statement

Context

AllLife Bank is a US bank that has a growing customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying sizes of deposits. The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans. In particular, the management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio.

You as a Data scientist at AllLife bank have to build a model that will help the marketing department to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability of purchasing the loan.

Objective

To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases, and identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customers age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: the Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have securities account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Online: Do customers use internet banking facilities? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All life Bank)? (0: No, 1: Yes)

Model Building

link text### Model Evaluation Criterion

In[]:
#using sklearn compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model
def model_perf_class_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

def display_confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")
In[]:
def show_feature_importance(importances, indices, feature_names):
  '''
  Description: Function to plot the features in the order of importance
  Parameters:
    importances: sklearn.tree.DecisionTreeClassifier, required
      The DataFrame of the two-dimensional tabular data

    indices: numpy.ndarray, required
      The indices of array

    feature_names: list, required
      The column names of features
  '''
  plt.figure(figsize = (12, 5))
  plt.title('Feature Importances', fontsize = 11)
  plt.barh(range(len(indices)), importances[indices], color = 'violet', align = 'center')
  plt.yticks(range(len(indices)), [feature_names[i] for i in indices])
  plt.xlabel('Relative Importance')

  plt.show()

Observations :-

  • The model achieves perfect performance (100%) on the training data, suggesting that it has memorized the training set.
  • However, when evaluated on the test data, performance drops, especially in recall (0.88591) and F1-score (0.89796).This suggests that the model overfits to the training data, meaning it may struggle with generalization.
  • The accuracy drops from 1.0 on training data to 0.98 on test data, which is a slight but notable decrease.
  • The recall (ability to correctly identify positive cases) drops more significantly from 1.0 to 0.88591, meaning some positive instances are being missed.
  • Precision is relatively high at 0.91034, indicating that when the model predicts a positive case, it is mostly correct.
  • The class_weight can be utilized to adjust the weighting calculations of the model.

    • Precision measures how many of the predicted loan takers were actually correct.
    • A high precision means fewer false positives, which is crucial for ensuring that only actual potential loan customers are targeted.
    • The 91% precision suggests the model is very effective at avoiding unnecessary loan approvals.

  • Recall (88.00%in Test and 95.16% in Train dataset)

    • Recall represents the proportion of actual loan takers correctly identified.
    • The recall of 88% means 12% of actual loan customers were missed, which could result in lost revenue opportunities for the bank.
    • Compared to precision, recall is slightly lower, indicating a conservative approach in predicting loan takers.

Post Pruning

In[122]:
# Train an overfitted tree to find optimal pruning parameter (ccp_alpha)
model_post_pruned = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1)
model_post_pruned.fit(X_train, Y_train)

# Get cost complexity pruning path
path = model_post_pruned.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train, Y_train)
ccp_alphas = path.ccp_alphas

# Train and evaluate models with different alpha values
pruned_models = []
accuracies = []

for alpha in ccp_alphas[:-1]:  # Exclude last value as it prunes everything
    pruned_tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1, ccp_alpha=alpha)
    pruned_tree.fit(X_train, Y_train)
    y_pred_pruned = pruned_tree.predict(X_test)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(Y_test, y_pred_pruned)
    pruned_models.append(pruned_tree)
    accuracies.append(accuracy)

# Identify best alpha
best_alpha_index = accuracies.index(max(accuracies))
best_alpha = ccp_alphas[best_alpha_index]
best_pruned_tree = pruned_models[best_alpha_index]

# Print best ccp_alpha value
print(f"The best ccp_alpha value for optimal post-pruning is: {best_alpha:.6f}")

# Plot Alpha vs Accuracy
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.plot(ccp_alphas[:-1], accuracies, marker="o", linestyle="--")
plt.xlabel("Alpha (ccp_alpha)")
plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
plt.title("Post-Pruning: Alpha vs. Model Accuracy")
plt.show()

# Final Evaluation of the Best Pruned Tree
y_pred_best_pruned = best_pruned_tree.predict(X_test)
accuracy_best_pruned = accuracy_score(Y_test, y_pred_best_pruned)

# Display Pruned Tree

plot_tree(best_pruned_tree, feature_names=X.columns, class_names=['No Loan', 'Loan'], filled=True)

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations

  1. Income :-

Customers with income above $100K are far more likely to accept a personal loan. Higher-income customers are financially stable and may take loans for investments, luxury purchases, or business purposes.

  1. Credit Card Spending :-

Customers spending above $2K/month on credit cards show a higher likelihood of taking loans. This suggests they are comfortable using credit and may require additional liquidity.

  1. Customers with CD Accounts :-

Holding a Certificate of Deposit (CD) account correlates with higher loan acceptance. These customers trust the bank and may be open to bundled financial products.

  1. Higher Education Increases Loan Acceptance

Customers with Graduate or Advanced degrees are more likely to take loans. These customers tend to have stable jobs and higher earning potential, making them ideal candidates.

  1. Online Banking Users Show Higher Engagement

Customers who actively use online banking are more likely to accept a loan. Digital engagement suggests openness to automated, paperless loan offers.

  1. Mortgage Holders Show Some Interest in Loans

Customers with existing mortgages may be interested in home improvement or refinancing loans. However, mortgage size alone is not the best predictor of loan acceptance.

Business Recoomendations

Loan Campaign :-

  • Use predictive analytics to focus on high-income earners, credit card spenders, and CD account holders.
  • Prioritize these customers for loan pre-approvals with competitive rates.

Segmented Marketing Messages :-

  • High-Income Professionals: Offer loans for investments, education, or business expansion.
  • Online Banking Users: Display loan offers within the mobile banking app for easy application.
  • Mortgage Holders: Promote home improvement loans or refinancing options.

Flexible Interest Rate Options :-

  • Provide tiered interest rates based on income and credit history to attract high-quality borrowers.

Instant Digital Loan Approvals :-

  • Enable a seamless digital application process for online banking users.
  • Use a pre-approval system based on customer spending and income patterns.

Strengthen Customer Engagement & Awareness :-

  • Proactive Outreach via Relationship Managers

    • Assign personal banking advisors to high-value customers.

Bundle Loan Offers with CD Accounts :-

  • Offer preferential loan rates for customers with CD accounts.
